                                                                                                                                 2                                                                                      End of Cuttack flood woes in sight
          OUR CORRESPONDENT                          Relief soon: Flooded streets of Cuttack                                  
	Cuttack, Feb. 21: The Naveen Patnaik government has drawn up a blueprint to end the inundation trauma of the city during heavy rains.        
	The Orissa Water Supply and Sewerage Board, under the housing and urban development department, will come up with a state-of-the-art sewerage system.        
	This will facilitate smooth drainage of stormwater into the rivers during heavy rainfall and free citizens from the woes and miseries of sewerage problem vis--vis reducing the problems of inundation in low-lying areas of the city.        
	Housing and urban development secretary Arun Kumar Panda said: It will be a Rs 757.44-crore integrated sanitation project funded by the Japanese government. Detailed survey and planning have already started. Construction is scheduled to start towards the end of 2011 and will be completed by the end of 2014.        
	Of the Rs 757.44 crore project cost, the Japanese government will fund Rs 624.65 crore through Japan International Co-operation Agency as loan assistance and the rest will be borne by the state.         
	Housing and urban development minister Badrinarayan Patra said: The loan will be repaid by the state government in 40 years with a moratorium period of 10 years with an interest rate of 0.75 per cent per annum.        
	The project is being implemented with the support of a project management consultant consortium of Tokyo Engineering Consultants Company, Tetra Tech Inc of the US and Egis BCEOM International of France.                                                                                                                                                           
